{"title_page": "Haminu Draman", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Haminu Draman\n| image          = Haminu.JPG\n| image_size      = 300px\n| caption        = Haminu Draman playing for [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban]]\n| fullname       = Haminu Draman\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1986|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Techiman]], Ghana\n| height         = {{convert|1.73|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    =           |youthclubs1 =\n| years1         = 2004\u20132005 |clubs1  = [[Heart of Lions]]                       |caps1  = 3   |goals1  = 0\n| years2         = 2005\u20132006 |clubs2  = [[Red Star Belgrade]]                    |caps2  = 4   |goals2  = 1\n| years3         = 2006\u20132007 |clubs3  = [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.|Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi]]   |caps3  = 31  |goals3  = 2\n| years4         = 2007\u20132011 |clubs4  = [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] |caps4  = 8   |goals4  = 0\n| years5         = 2009      |clubs5  = \u2192 [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban]] (loan)    |caps5  = 27  |goals5  = 3\n| years6         = 2011\u20132013 |clubs6  = [[AC Arles-Avignon|Arles-Avignon]]       |caps6  = 30  |goals6  = 2\n| years7         = 2013\u20132014 |clubs7  = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]         |caps7  = 3   |goals7  = 0\n| years8         = 2014      |clubs8  = [[Asante Kotoko SC|Asante Kotoko]]       |caps8  =     |goals8  =\n| years9         = 2015      |clubs9  = [[Charlotte Independence]]               |caps9  = 2   |goals9  = 0\n| years10        = 2016      |clubs10 = [[FC Infonet|Infonet]]                   |caps10 = 23  |goals10 = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132010 |nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] |nationalcaps1 = 43 |nationalgoals1 = 4\n| pcupdate       = 13 June 2017\n| ntupdate       = 13 June 2017\n}}\n\n'''Haminu Draman''' (born 1 April 1986)<ref>https://ghanasoccernet.com/player-profiles?player=620</ref> is a Ghanaian [[Association football|footballer]].\n\n==Club career==\nHaving started his career in Ghana with [[Heart of Lions F.C.]], Draman joined Serbian club [[Red Star Belgrade]] for the [[2005\u201306 First League of Serbia and Montenegro|2005\u201306]]. Having won the championship and the cup with Red Star moved to Turkey, where he made 31 league appearances for [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.]] as they finished sixth in the Turkish [[Turkcell Super League|S\u00fcper Lig]].\n\nDraman signed a three-year contract with Russian Cup winners [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] on 19 June 2007. Draman joined Lokomotiv when the Russian transfer window opened on 1 August 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Draman's the man for Lokomotiv |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=552834.html |website=UEFA.com |accessdate=29 April 2020 |date=19 June 2007}}</ref> He was expected to replace Russian international [[Marat Izmailov]], who is on loan to Portuguese club [[Sporting Lisbon]] for a year.\n\nFollowing the transfer of Draman Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi's coach [[Ersun Yanal]] quit after just over a week in charge because he disagreed with the club's decision.<ref>{{cite news | date=9 June 2007 |url=http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=549284.html | title=Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi hit by Yanal U-turn | publisher=UEFA | accessdate=9 June 2007}}</ref> Yanal, who had previously been coach of Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi before leaving to become the [[Turkey national football team|Turkish national team]] coach, had signed a three-year contract with the club on 1 June 2007. \"The chairman's promises seem to have changed from the way they were before the agreement we made\" Yanal said. \"We would like to be a strong team but we sold Draman. The club want to try some players on trial in the meantime but this is not the way that I work.<ref>{{cite news | date=19 June 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/6768229.stm | title=Dramani moves to Russia | publisher=BBC | accessdate=19 June 2007}}</ref> Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi chairman Cavcav, who had been in charge of the club for 30 years, responded by saying: \"We met with the coach before and then I told him that I have to sell Draman to Locomotiv Moskva because all of the negotiations were over and I promised to sell him.<ref>{{cite news | date=11 June 2007 | url=http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=75496 | title=Coach departure induces fan protest at Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi | publisher=Turkish Daily News | accessdate=11 June 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171102/http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=75496 | archivedate=30 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that English [[Premier League|Premiership]] side [[Stoke City]] were interested in signing Draman because of his speed and skills in the January 2008 transfer window, and that a fee of \u20ac3 million had been agreed.<ref>{{cite news | date=18 November 2008 | url=http://www.mtnfootball.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=17225 | title=Ghana's Draman Set For England | publisher=MTN Football | accessdate=18 November 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119032118/http://mtnfootball.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=17225 | archivedate=19 November 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February 2009, Draman signed for [[FC Kuban Krasnodar]] on loan from Lokomotiv Moscow.<ref>[http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_3268/ Draman to Kuban] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719085619/http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_3268/ |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2011, Draman signed a one-year contract with French [[Ligue 2]] side [[AC Arles-Avignon]].<ref>{{cite news | date=12 July 2011 |url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-midfielder-haminu-dramani-joins-french-side-arles-avignon/ | title=Ghana midfielder Haminu Dramani joins French side Arles Avignon | publisher=GHANAsoccernet.com | accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Draman signed a two-year contract for Portuguese club [[Gil Vicente F.C.]] on a free transfer.<ref name=\"gil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-winger-haminu-dramani-signs-two-deal-with-gil-vicente-on-a-free-transfer | title=Ghana winger Haminu Dramani signs two-deal with Gil Vicente on a free transfer | publisher = ghanasoccernet.com | accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref> This was after he had left Arles Avignon due to unpaid salary.<ref name=\"gil\"/>\n\nDraman left Gil Vicente during the winter-break, and by early 2014, he was back in Ghana, after almost a decade, by signing with [[Asante Kotoko S.C.]] His return turned out to be a great success as he won the double, the [[2013\u201314 Ghanaian Premier League]] and the 2014 [[Ghanaian FA Cup]] during his half-year spell with Asante Kotoko back in Ghana.<ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT|11613|name=Haminu Draman|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe signed for [[FC Infonet]] in January 2016.<ref>[http://jalgpall.ee/fprotocol.php?st=style_fp.css&proto=1188&b=]</ref> With 3 goals in 23 appearances he helped them win their first ever national title, the [[2016 Meistriliiga]].<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n==International career==\nDraman was 19 when he made his international debut for Ghana in a friendly against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in [[Riyadh]] on 14 November 2005. He is a member of the [[Ghana national football team|national team]], and was called up to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. He scored his first goal of the tournament against the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S.]] on 22 June 2006.\n\nHe took a starring role in Ghana's International friendly against former World Champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] on 27 March 2007 where the Ghanaians lost 1\u20130, terrorising the Samba Boys right back [[Ilsinho]], before being dismissed late in the game for a second bookable offence on Ilsinho's replacement [[Daniel Alves]].\n\n====Note on name====\nThere was some confusion during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] as Draman's surname was misspelled DRAMANI on the back of his shirt and, as a result, on [[FIFA]] documents. The Ghanaian FA confirm his name is Draman. He has also confirmed this himself in an interview to ''[[Sport Express]],'' a Russian newspaper.<ref>[http://www.sport-express.ru/newspaper/2007-07-04/1_2 \u0425\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u0414\u0420\u0410\u041c\u0410\u041d: \"\u041f\u041e\u041f\u0420\u041e\u0428\u0423 \u0423\u0411\u0420\u0410\u0422\u042c \u0411\u0423\u041a\u0412\u0423 \"\u0418\" \u0421 \u0424\u0423\u0422\u0411\u041e\u041b\u041a\u0418. \u042f \u2013 \u0414\u0420\u0410\u041c\u0410\u041d\"]</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{{Updated|match played 11 August 2010}}<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]]\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2005||1||0\n|-\n|2006||12||2\n|-\n|2007||4||0\n|-\n|2008||14||1\n|-\n|2009||7||1\n|-\n|2010||5||0\n|-\n!Total||43||4\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Ghana's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!Goal!!Date!!Venue!!Opponent!!Score!!Result!!Competition!!Ref\n|-\n|1 ||22 June 2006||[[Frankenstadion]], [[Nuremberg]], Germany||{{fb|United States}}||<center>1\u20130</center>||<center>2\u20131</center>||[[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E]]||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 2-1 USA|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=97410100/match=97410042/index.html#nosticky|website=fifa.com|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=7 July 2016|date=22 June 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|2 ||4 October 2006||[[International Stadium Yokohama|Nissan Stadium]], [[Yokohama]], Japan||{{fb|Japan}}||<center>1\u20130</center>||<center>1\u20130</center>||[[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]||<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan 0-1 Ghana|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/matches/report/13878/Japan_Ghana.html|website=national-football-teams.com|publisher=National Football Teams|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|3 ||9 February 2008||[[Baba Yara Stadium]], [[Kumasi]], Ghana||{{fb|Ivory Coast}}||<center>4\u20132</center>||<center>4\u20132</center>||Friendly||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 4-2 Ivory Coast|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/matches/report/1239/Ghana_Ivory_Coast.html|website=national-football-teams.com|publisher=National Football Teams|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|3 ||12 August 2009||[[Brisbane Road]], London, England||{{fb|Zambia}}||<center>4\u20131</center>||<center>4\u20131</center>||Friendly||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 4-1 Zambia|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/matches/report/11869/Ghana_Zambia.html|website=national-football-teams.com|publisher=National Football Teams|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Red Star Belgrade'''\n*[[First League of Serbia and Montenegro]]: [[2005\u201306 First League of Serbia and Montenegro|2005\u201306]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n*[[Serbia and Montenegro Cup]]: [[2005\u201306 Serbia and Montenegro Cup|2006]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n'''Lokomotiv Moscow'''\n*[[Russian Cup (football)|Russian Cup]]: 2007<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n'''Asante Kotoko'''\n*[[Ghana Premier League]]: [[2013\u201314 Ghanaian Premier League|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n*[[Ghanaian FA Cup]]: 2014<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n'''Infonet'''\n*[[Meistriliiga]]: [[2016 Meistriliiga|2016]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n===International===\n'''Ghana'''\n*[[Africa Cup of Nations]]: [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]] (runner-up)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/player/235367_DRAMAN_Haminu.html Fifa 2006 World Cup Prof